I just had a look into glib's source and as far as I can see, there is only one way to get a call to g_log directly from g_malloc_n and that's by causing an overflow:

~~~
gpointer
g_malloc_n (gsize n_blocks,
	    gsize n_block_bytes)
{
  if (SIZE_OVERFLOWS (n_blocks, n_block_bytes))
    {
      g_error ("%s: overflow allocating %"G_GSIZE_FORMAT"*%"G_GSIZE_FORMAT" bytes",
               G_STRLOC, n_blocks, n_block_bytes);
    }

  return g_malloc (n_blocks * n_block_bytes);
}
~~~

So in other words, `gdk_cairo_set_source_pixbuf` tries to allocate a weird amount of memory to draw some icon?

